```suggestion
theorem _root_.FirstOrder.Language.Formula.realize_iInf [Finite Î²] {f : Î² â†’ L.Formula Î±}
    {v : Î± â†’ M} : (Formula.iInf f).Realize v â†” âˆ€ b, (f b).Realize v := by
```
same above

```suggestion
/-- Take the disjunction of finitely many formulas. -/
```
Same below

Do we need this? `Formula` is an `abbrev` for `BoundedFormula`, so `BoundedFormula.iSup`/`BoundedFormula.iInf` does everything you new definitions already do (and your new definitions aren't `abbrev`s)

I don't know. Personally I think that the current `BoundedFormula` and `Formula` duplication is quite annoying but so far we do seem to have been duplicating a lot of things (but the library is not completely consistent). `BoundedFormula` can be a bit anooying to use when reasoning about semantics because for a `BoundedFormula L Î± 0` you have this term `Fin 0 -> M` at the end when you use `BoundedFormula.realize` which are always equal obviously, but not necessarily definitionally equal.

The best long term solution in my view is probably to claim that `BoundedFormula` is just an implementation detail and we should basically always be using `Formula` and we just have to introduce a single variable `all` and `ex` on formulas and the exact type of these definitions I'm not sure of. I don't have a strong opinion on any temporary fix before that.

I agree that there's some major cleanup that needs to happen in the long term - I wish I had a concrete suggestion for how it should go.

In the meantime, do you have a use case for `iSup` or `iInf` for `Formula`s as opposed to `BoundedFormula`s? Is it possible that we could even remove the `BoundedFormula` version and just work with `Formula`s now?

I'm personally fine having both if there's actual code that works better that way while awaiting a good general solution to duplication.

I almost never used `BoundedFormula`, I think mainly because I was very rarely quantifying over a single variable, it was always over an arbitrary finite number of variables.

A use case for iInf is the statement of Ax Grothendieck. It's about injectivity and surjectivity of maps K^n -> K^n and I needed iInf to state equality of elements of K^n

Do you want to use anonymous dot notation here? Something like
```suggestion
    ((Ï†.relabel (Sum.elim (.inl âˆ˜ .inl) .inr)).imp
    (.iInf fun g => Term.equal (var (.inr g)) (var (.inl (.inr g))))))
```
and maybe also use `<|` more
I've done some of this
